{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486646"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"151"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/151"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.23,0.06,0.19,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54329"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/151"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39836"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1317"},{"type":"tags","id":"3049"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54329"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department two hours after an intentional medication overdose.\u00a0He has a known history of depression and takes citalopram 20mg daily. He lives at home with his older brother who has chronic schizophrenia and who takes haloperidol 10mg daily. It appears that the younger brother took one packet (20 tablets) of medication, however it is not known which medication this was. On examination he appears sweaty, confused and agitated. His blood pressure is 150/105 mmHg, pulse 120/min and regular, temperature 39.1\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and Sp02 98% on room air. Neurological examination reveals bilateral dilated pupils, bilateral fine tremor, generalised hyperreflexia, and sustained ankle clonus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to supportive care, which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diazepam","Bromocriptine","Phenobarbitone","Dantrolene","Activated charcoal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case of medication overdose presents with symptoms consistent with serotonin syndrome, a toxic state due to excess serotonin in the central nervous system, likely due to an overdose of the patient\u2019s regular citalopram. Treatment includes cessation of all serotonergic medication, primary survey with optimal oxygenation, supportive care with intravenous hydration, temperature control and careful monitoring of vitals and fluid status. Benzodiazepines (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Ediazepam\u003C/strong\u003E) are used for sedation, relief of agitation and maintenance of vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for gastrointestinal detoxification, with most guidelines suggesting it may be used within 4 hours of ingestion. However, in this case, the patient has presented with features of serotonin syndrome that must be managed as a priority - charcoal might be administered, but not as the first step and is rarely used in practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDantrolene\u003C/strong\u003E is a direct-acting skeletal muscle relaxant and is used in the management of the neuroleptic malignant syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBromocriptine\u003C/strong\u003E has many uses and has roles in the management of neuroleptic malignant syndrome, acromegaly, Parkinson\u0027s, hyperprolactinaemia and glycaemic control in type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenobarbitone\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in epilepsy (although would not be first line), but it does not have a role in the management of serotonin syndrome outside of seizure activity.  \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzodiazepines have a first-line role in the management of serotonin syndrome."],"references":["Boyer EW, Shannon M. The serotonin syndrome [published correction appears in N Engl J Med. 2007 Jun 7;356(23):2437] [published correction appears in N Engl J Med. 2009 Oct 22;361(17):1714].\u00a0N Engl J Med. 2005;352(11):1112-1120. doi:10.1056/NEJMra041867"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39836"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"151"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39836"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T09:18:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T09:19:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"151"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54329"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":nul